{
  "text": "Transmission electron microscopy images of polymersomes are shown in Figure 3 (a: low-magnification, b: high-magnification). Mean thickness of the hydrophobic core of the wall was around 4 nm, which is similar to the size of integral membrane protein [CITATION_1] . However, the thickness of free-standing planar membrane was measured to be about 9 nm by electrochemical impedance spectroscopy [CITATION_2] . The observed thickness difference between polymersomes and planar membranes may be attributed to shape-dependent conformation change of the polymer molecules or errors in thickness estimation based on capacitance measurement. In discussing the thickness of the hydrophobic layer of polymersomes, critical factors are thought to be: molecular weight of the hydrophobic block, conformation of the copolymer, and polydispersity. Battaglia and Ryan derived the thickness of the hydrophobic layer of block copolymer vesicles using a power law:",
  "correct_citation": {
